>but the desert stoner bands like Kyuss, Fu Manchu, and Sleep were very influenced by bands like Soundgarden and Mudhoney
Sleep were hesher kids that were too obsessed SINGULARLY with Sabbath, I doubt they listened to grunge, metalheads mostly hated it back in the day. Still do. They somewhat liked Melvins but that's not 'grunge' in spite of the revisionism.
Kyuss were hardcore punk kids from the desert who got influenced by '70s rock through the leader of their local Palm Desert punk scene, Mario Lalli, who had a really eclectic taste and listened to just about everything, including stuff punks hated like '70s hard rock, and his tastes rubbed off on Homme, Brant Bjork, etc. Josh Homme said when he first heard Nirvana and Soundgarden he thought they were ripping off Across The River (Mario's band in the 80s)
Fu Manchu were pretty much a sister band to Kyuss, so the same applies.

I like Soundgarden, Lanegan and AIC, but the Seattle scene itself only influenced trash sadly

Thanks for the feedback.
I think the chords are ok. But I have to say my personal taste has low tolerance for le sad junkie vibes and shoegaze. I can’t tell but I think there are some synth strings in the background, I think you have to be careful with those or they can be quite hammy.

The melody is slow and buried in effects so I can’t really judge it but you should be careful as that sort of sound is recorded in bedrooms daily for the last 15 years. The lyric subject I don’t personally like but I do think they have a poetic sense to them that is better than average. I’d probably be less on the nose with the lyrics subject wise if you wanted to attempt to be artistic but that’s My opinion only.

In my opinion, and it’s only mine, if you write a song it should work as a simple acoustic / piano piece and vocals, and as a rockabilly before you start adding anything to the song production wise. It’s a litmus test to make sure the melody and chords and words are good and it’s not a meh song being buried in production.
Guns (like the vocals or not) is a bit different because it’s not really pop music even with the poppy melodies It’s unidirectional and doesn’t repeat or cycle hooks and the instrumentation itself is a large part of the experience. It’s not just chords and a melody on repeat. It builds to a climax and then declines.

I think your song by contrast is fine and has some competency in production and mix but perhaps you could push it another level to make something that stands out more from the Field. Many pick up a guitar and a laptop and lay down a few chords and a melody and lyrics about drugs. It’s a tough place to compete in. All I’m saying. Even if you’re the best at it it’s going to be hard to be noticed.
Of course make what you like, just my take.

this could be roughly translated as

For anyone interested in Germany it is very well known that the Horst Wessel Lied and main symbolisms used by Goebbels are tighly linked with each other.

You could have a setup where you plug one of the dongles into your guitar, the other into line in on the audio interface; then the wireless headphones into the monitoring out port on the interface; and the only wire involved would be the USB cable from the interface to your computer. See picrel

>>114596112
Why wouldn't this be feasible? The answer of course, is latency. Now normally, there's already a bit of latency even with a completely wired setup:
1. guitar->interface is going analog->digital
2. interface+computer process the sound digitally and send it to monitor out
3. interface->monitor out goes digital->analog, and finally to your headphones

Maybe something like 5ms or 12ms, which is still low enough to be fine & unnoticeable.
This is because we're only doing one full "round trip" so to speak, from the analog of the guitar, to digital so the computer can process it, and back to analog for your headphones.

But with this wireless setup we're going through a bunch more conversions unnecessarily:
1. guitar->wireless 1/4" system (ADC); dongles transmit digital signal over 2.4ghz
2. wireless receiver->interface's line in (DAC)
3. interface+computer process sound digitally
4. interface->monitor out jack (ADC)
5. wireless headphone base station now transmits a digital signal to the headphones via 2.4ghz (same as the wireless guitar dongles do)
6. finally, headphones convert that signal to analog for the drivers (DAC) and into ur ears

I've heard even the good wireless guitar dongles add something like 10ms or so, but that's usually fine since they're designed for & expected to be used directly with an amp. The wireless headphones supposedly also add their own 16ms - also fine assuming you're using the headphones with just your PC, where everything starts as digital to begin with.

But combining these all together: the dongles + interface processing time + headphones is something like 10+12+16ms = 38ms or more, which veers into the unnacceptable range of latency.

>>114596123
My question is, why hasn't this been addressed with an audio interface that's explicitly designed to be wireless from the ground up? It would probably end up needing some specific proprietary pieces, like an included guitar adapter designed to be made with the interface only; and headphones also designed to work specifically with the interface. But it could be something like:

An interface with a built-in wireless module that connects to a (single) included dongle you plug into your guitar. This would convert the analog guitar signal to a digital stream right inside the dongle, and transmit that to the interface unit's (digital) wireless chip. Now you have a digital signal that gets processed by the computer and back to the interface. At this point the wireless module would also communicate with wireless headphones, that also have their own DAC chip to do the final digital->analog conversion. The advantage here is we've only done one "round trip", same as before if we were using wires and any old traditional audio interface on the market. It's just that the conversions between analog don't take place inside the unit itself, but are rather "pushed out" into both the guitar dongle, and the DAC inside the headphones.

I'm sure it's possible, just hasn't been done. Why not though? I'm sure some rich fucks would pay the premium for total cable-less freedom.

>Audio engineering is how the overall recordings sound but the engineers don't know the creative side of making songs.
Some do - a lot of them started out as engineers, and moved into producing after learning the ropes and making the right connections. Jack Douglas started out as a janitor at the Record Plant in NYC, then learned to be an engineer, worked on big albums for tons of people, including the Who's Lifehouse stuff, then Bob Ezrin convinced him to try producing, and he went on to produce Aerosmith, John Lennon on Double Fantasy, and tons more. Ken Calliat, who did Rumors, was an engineer and producer his whole career.
It's very unusual to start out right off the bat producing, unless it's with a band who brings you in. Most of them were musicians, or A/R, or engineers, who proved they could handle the gig.

>>114563849
The loudness you get depends on how much bandwith each element in your mix uses. In the case of your example, its a extremely barebones track with really nothing in the mids and highs so sonny can just smash that shit into a clipper really hard without it starting to pump or distort.

You would not get this sort of loudness with a very lush and rich sounding track without it sounding distorted in parts or without lowend or highend ducking.

In your case, you should start lowcutting and highcutting instruments. Like sub bass that doesnt need alot of top end and leads and instruments that doesnt need low end.

Also learn to use a clipper.

>>114563849
Listen here, I'll tell you how to compete in the loudness war. Go to each individual sound in your track and analyse it with an oscilloscope. If you see peaks in the waveform get rid of them with a clipper or limiter, but listen carefully to not overdo it. As soon as the sound changes back off, we don't want to change the sound only get rid of those little peaks. Do this also on your bus channels and on the master channel, before the compressors in the signal chain. You probably have to bounce those tracks due to the amount of clippers/limiters needed to give your CPU some relief. If you bounce those tracks remember to use the highest oversampling option.

If done correctly you'll have so much more headroom on the master channel with almost no audible difference in sound, your compressors will work more smoothly without those peaks and with your last limiter you'd be able to push hard for loudness. See pic and compare the numbers in the red boxes.

I was wondering the following, which, perhaps someone here can provide an answer.

Let's say an album has 9 songs (all the same genre, style, feel, etc.). In order for them to sound consistent and similar to one another, is it customary to mix one track and use that as the sort of "template" when mixing the rest? For example, saving EQ, reveb, etc. settings for a crash cymbal in one song and then just simply applying those same settings to the crash cymbal in the next song? And the same for snare, etc.? And then of course, could that same principle be applied to guitars, vocals, etc. etc. etc.?

posts.com:
>>114568120
pls /prod/, I'm this close to releasing

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114568171
No, each song should be mixed individually. Sound choice is probably more important than mixing. So you are making a conscious decision in the production to create a consistent and cohesive sound for an album. You limit yourself in terms of drum kits, drum machine, instruments, synths, mic...
You can of course copy some mixing tools for example using the same room reverb so it sounds like all tracks were recorded in the same room. Or using the same plugins with their specific characters like compressors, color EQ, saturation and so on. But the mixing process itself should be individual, don't limit yourself to a "template" of another song.

Mastering is something else. Here you are doing subtle changes and it is common to A/B test and use other songs of the album as a reference to create the final touches for a cohesive sound.

first step, chain mastering.
For each master channel and its bus use some sort of soft compresion, not too much it will add up later. Or call it chain compresion.

second step: or step 1.5
>>114563915
>start lowcutting and highcutting instruments
this is very important, drums and bass always fight with each other, at least the kick and bass.

step 2:
keep enough headroom in your production, watch for spikes they might fuck you up later in the mastering proces. You can do a little mastering during the production process but keep these two stages seperated.
Consolodate the final track and start to master on the clean wave file. If done right there should be no spikes fucking you up and a lot of headroom to fill it.

step 3:
most website compress your audio, for example youtube is compresion audio down to -3db (as far as i remember), keep this in mind.

fuck the loudness war

Not true btw

Not sure how DAWs handle it today but I learned that clipping (analog and digital) gives your artifacts/aliasing in your recording and there is no way to fix this after you exported your file.
You fuck up your frequency measurements and they become unreliable, which could cause a problem when you upload your track to some streaming service and they put their own algorithm on it.

>>114584762
that's just his style, man. You will noodle a lot over all those examples anyway, so why not do variations of them while your at it?
SNSs give you all the jazzy patterns and fingerings (a monumental effort, if you ask me). It's up to you to figure out how to play them all over the fretboard while visualizing them, with your own version of rhythms, time-feel, syncopation, etc and finally get it into your playing. And all that's just volume 1. Volume 2 is when you really use all those to play over changes.
Ted's method may look dull and uninspiring but its anti-lazyfagging and you get as much as you put in. If you are diligent enough by the end of vol1 you will know all of the positions by heart (along with a nice batch of corresponding voicings) and be able to read music on guitar. I wish i had gone through it slower and not skimming the most interesting lines which are lydian dominant and 3 types of altered dom scales

No, but now it's just a style. In the 1960s garage rock was organic, by Americans who were into the British Invasion but wanted to make more primal, aggressive music. In the 80s and 90s garage punk was one of the more vibrant underground scenes, all passionate bar bands. In the 00s that led to the garage rock revival in the mainstream, and was actually a pretty cool scene, with some real rockstar types like Jack White, Pete Doherty, and Karen O. Nowadays garage rock is just another indie scene, and none of the bands are doing anything all that interesting, with a few incredible exceptions like Tropical Fuck Storm.

Nowadays so many teens are into 00s garage rock revival bands like The Strokes and Arctic Monkeys that I'm pretty sure soon there'll be some kind of a garage rock revival revival.

i lived and played in the original garage rock revival in the mid to late 80's. you could argue that was actually the 3rd one.
the 1st true Garage rock were bands of kids in literal garages with shit equipment trying to play pop songs of the harmony groups with guitars like they were on the produced record at the time. They sounded rough and primitive because that is a consequence of the environment and materials not a conscious style.
then you could argue the first revival was in 1970 with the Stooges which in turn influenced all the other 'punk bands' of the mid to late 70's but if you ask me, and i am knowledgeable because i was there, this was merely a continuation of the original 'garage' (it wasn't termed that yet) sound that the punk kids gravitated towards for various reasons namely their class and abilities but especially the low fi DIY aesthetic.
So the Strokes and White Stripes Vines the Hives thing was truly the 3rd revival of 'Garage Rock' and was a decent one. A bit more refined than the mid-late '80's i lived and played through, which leaned heavily more 'Mod', where the lp Nuggets and Hush Puppies and Scooters and Brian Jones haircuts were essential and almost a comical anti fashion to the hair bands and powerballad overwrought dance shit. lot of milquetoast bands then and it peaked and was done overnight it seemed when the Velvet Underground got back together and it sucked.

>How do I bridge the gap between simply knowing the scale and using it?
Use the scales you learned to create melodic ideas over some chords. Take any song you like, let's say Hotel California, and create small motifs over the chords. Limits are the key, i.e. 3 notes maximum, only 3rds and 5ths, and so on... the objective of this is to make your scale sound like a melody, it has to make sense, to convey a concrete idea and the key to that is rhythm. You have the notes, the next step is to practice where to place them, and less is more in those terms. Two notes correctly placed can tell more than 10 scales stuffed in 2 bars. Silence is now the tool to learn.

posts.com:
>>114588168
Scales allow you to identify notes that will sound good when you base a song around a root note. It also trains your ear to hear this so it becomes automatic.

So when you're listening to an unfamiliar song and try to transcribe it, the thought process becomes
>okay lets find the root note on the instrument
>okay it's a D. And this other bit of the riff sounds like an F
>so if the root note is D and there's an F, chances are it's in the key of D minor
>that means I now know the 12 notes that are likely to be in this song. So there's unlikely to be a D#, for example
>now I can reverse engineer the song much more easily by just sticking to the D minor scale in different octaves

It also trains your fingers to play sequential notes to the point of muscle memory.

And, as you mentioned, it's helpful for improvising. So if you're jamming with someone playing and A chord or whatever, you know you can stick in the scale of A and it'll sound all right. E.g. as a bass player you can stick to the first, fourth and fifth notes of the scale or something

Frank Zappa Meets the Mothers of Prevention. I had heard What's New in Baltimore, of course, but hadn't listened to the full album. Several tracks that would fit right in Jazz from Hell, and the opener is a great Johnny Guitar Watson number. Last track is the PMRC hearing.

If you like Jazz from Hell, you will like most of this record. What's New in Baltimore is one of Frank and Vai's best works ever, other than Drowning Witch, but I don't think Vai was with the group at this point. I think this was Frank's last non-classical studio album, could be wrong about it. This came out a few years before his disastrous '88 tour.
